war scientific programs including the Space Race, atmospheric and underground nuclear testing, and geological expeditions such as Project Mohole (which attempted to drill to the earth's mantle). As Whitmarsh argues, by focusing readers' attention on the fragility of postwar life through a vertical lens, Anthropocene fiction highlights the interconnections between human behavior and planetary change. These fictions situate industrial history within the much longer narrative of geological time and reframe scientific progress as a story through which humankind writes itself out of existence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aAmerican fictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aAmerican fictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEcoliterature, American2DLC. 0aEcoliterature, American. 0aExtinction (Biology) in literature2DLC. 0aExtinction (Biology) in literature. 0aGeology in literature2DLC. 0aGeology in literature. 0aGlobal environmental change in literature2DLC. 0aGlobal environmental change in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aAmerican Fiction.  aAnthropocene.  aContemporary.  aEcocriticism.  aExtinction.  aHistory of Science.  aPost-1945.  aVerticality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023 Englishz978311131909408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Cultural and Area Studies 2023z978311131812708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru